  "summary": "Hercule Poirot reveals that the cyanide used to kill Polly Weatherby was not in a bag, as previously suspected, but was carried by the killer. After Tony Chapple retrieves a box of cyanide from Stephen Carter's chest pocket, Barton Russell accuses Carter of poisoning Eileen to avoid a scandal. However, Poirot intervenes to expose Russell as the true culprit.\n\nPoirot explains that during the darkness of the cabaret performance, Russell left his seat to act as a server, pouring champagne for the guests. While doing so, he placed cyanide in Polly's glass and planted the remaining cyanide box in Carter's pocket to frame him. Poirot identifies Russell's motive as financial; as Polly's guardian, Russell needed to secure her property once she turned twenty-one. To avoid a scandal, Polly decides not to sue Russell but insists that he leave the country. Russell departs the venue in an angry rage, insulting Poirot.\n\nPolly explains to Poirot that she had suspected Russell's scheme after noticing he had ordered yellow irises and an extra place setting for the dinner. She admits she had called Poirot using a forged, mysterious message to attract his attention because she felt an inexplicable sense of dread. Following the resolution, Carter leaves the gathering, while the remaining guests, including Poirot, Lola Valdes, Tony Chapple, and Vera, move to the dance floor.",
